```java
// Node class definition
class Node {
    int value; // This integer holds the data we want to store in each node.
    Node left; // Reference to the left child of the node.
    Node right; // Reference to the right child of the node.

    // Node class constructor
    Node(int value) {
        this.value = value; // Assign the value provided when creating the node.
        left = null;  // Initialize the left child as null (no child yet).
        right = null; // Initialize the right child as null (no child yet).
    }
}

// BinaryTree class definition
public class BinaryTree {

    Node root; // Reference to the root node of the tree (topmost node).

    // BinaryTree class constructor
    public BinaryTree() {
        root = null; // Initialize the root as null (no nodes in the tree initially).
    }

    // Recursive method to insert a value into the correct location in the binary tree
    private Node insertRecursive(Node current, int value) {
        if (current == null) {
            return new Node(value); // Create a new node with the value if we reach an empty spot.
        }
        if (value < current.value) {
            current.left = insertRecursive(current.left, value); // Recur on the left subtree.
        } else if (value > current.value) {
            current.right = insertRecursive(current.right, value); // Recur on the right subtree.
        } else {
            // Value already exists, do nothing.
            return current;
        }
        return current; // Return the (possibly updated) current node.
    }

    // Public method to start the insertion process
    public void insert(int value) {
        root = insertRecursive(root, value); // Start the recursive insert from the root.
    }

    // Method to perform an in-order traversal of the tree and print each node's value
    public void inOrderTraversal(Node node) {
        if (node != null) {
            inOrderTraversal(node.left); // Recur on the left child.
            System.out.print(node.value + " "); // Print the value of the node.
            inOrderTraversal(node.right); // Recur on the right child.
        }
    }

    // Main method - entry point to the program
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BinaryTree bt = new BinaryTree(); // Create a new BinaryTree object.

        // Insert nodes into the binary tree
        bt.insert(6);
        bt.insert(4);
        bt.insert(8);
        bt.insert(3);
        bt.insert(5);
        bt.insert(7);
        bt.insert(9);

        // Perform an in-order traversal of the binary tree and print out the values.
        bt.inOrderTraversal(bt.root);
    }
}
```

Here's a step-by-step explanation:

1. The `Node` class is the building block of the tree. Each `Node` carries a value and has two children: `left` and `right`.

2. The `BinaryTree` class wraps the `Node` and provides methods to manipulate the tree, such as `insert()` and `inOrderTraversal()`.

3. In the `insert()` method, we start the recursive process by calling `insertRecursive()` on the root of the tree with the new value.

4. The `insertRecursive()` method finds the correct spot for the new value by comparing it to the current node's value and going either left or right as needed until it finds an empty spot where a new node can be created.

5. The `inOrderTraversal()` method recursively traverses the tree in an in-order manner (left child, current node, right child) and prints the values in a sorted order.

6. In the `main` method, we create an instance of `BinaryTree` (bt), insert values into the tree, and finally print the values in the tree in an in-order sorted manner.

